organisms is most likely to be responsible?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clostridium perfringens","Escherichia coli","Salmonella sp","Staphylococcus aureus","Streptococcus pyogenes"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe photograph shows what is probably an area of inflammation around some local abscess formation in the wound. This is an inflammatory response and not cellulitis. \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EBacteroides spp \u003C/em\u003E(usually fragilis) are the two most common causes of post-operative wound infection, particularly when some part of the gastrointestinal tract has been opened. Of all the organisms mentions, \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli \u003C/em\u003Eis the most likely cause of the wound infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Estaphylococcal infections\u003C/strong\u003E are a common cause of dermal and subdermal abscesses and are the commonest cause of surgical wound infections in general, in these circumstances the infection is most likely to be due to a gut-derived organism - around 30% of wound infections that occur after colorectal surgery are due to\u003Cem\u003E E. coli, \u003C/em\u003Ecompared to about 7% of wound infections caused by \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EClostridium perfringens\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is a relatively common cause of food poisoning and when it does cause tissue infection, it usually leads to necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ESalmonella spp\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E do not cause wound infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of cellulitis rather than wound infection per se.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Escherichia coli and Bacteroides sp (usually fragilis) are the two most common causes of post-operative wound infections when some part of the gastrointestinal tract has been opened."],"references":["Young PY, Khadaroo RG. Surgical Site Infections. Surg Clin N Am 2014; 94:1245-64. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25440122/","Bargavi K, Secunda R, Saravanan J, Satyanesan J. Surgical Site Infections in Gastrointestinal Surgeries: Estimation of Prevalence, Risk Factors and Bacteriological Profile. Cureus. 2024 Jun 18;16(6):e62589. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11256213/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89852"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1918"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19808"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19808"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fbf2b439-eca7-452a-b995-d76eb14a476c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fbf2b439-eca7-452a-b995-d76eb14a476c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89852"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-29T10:43:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-29T10:43:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1918"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107366"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici